{{Infobox language |name = Kurbetcha |state = [[Cyprus]] |ethnicity = Kurbet (Cypriot Muslim Roma) |speakers = ? |familycolor = creole |family=[[Romani language|Romani]]–[[Turkish language|Turkish]] creole |iso3 = none |glotto=none }}
'''Kurbetcha''' (or '''Gurbetcha''') is a [[creole language]] with what appears to be predominantly [[Romani language|Romani]] vocabulary and [[Cypriot Turkish]] grammar, spoken by the ''Kurbet'' ([[Romani people|Roma]]) of [[Cyprus]]. The Kurbet have traditionally also spoken [[Turkish language|Turkish]]. The majority settled in the [[Northern Cyprus|north]] after [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|1974]], but many of those have returned to the south (i.e. the areas under the effective control of the Republic of Cyprus) in recent years.
Kurbetcha has been very little studied. Children are not learning the language; it has been supplanted by Turkish in the north and Greek in the south.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/14664208.2011.629113|last1=Hadjioannou|first1=Xenia|last2=Tsiplakou|first2=Stavroula|last3=Kappler|first3=Matthias|year=2011|title=Language policy and language planning in Cyprus|journal=Current Issues in Language Planning|volume=12|issue=4|pages=503–569|publisher=Routledge}}</ref>
