'''Richard Carew''' (17 July 1555 – 6 November 1620) was a [[Cornwall|Cornish]] [[translator]] and [[antiquary]]. He is best known for his [[English county histories|county history]], ''Survey of Cornwall'' (1602).

==Life==
Carew belonged to a prominent gentry family, and was the eldest son of [[Thomas Carew (MP for Saltash)|Thomas Carew]]: he was born on 17 July 1555 at [[Antony, Cornwall|East Antony]], Cornwall. He was educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], where he was a contemporary of Sir [[Philip Sidney]] and [[William Camden]], and then at the [[Middle Temple]]. He made a translation of the first five [[canto]]s of [[Torquato Tasso|Tasso]]'s ''[[Jerusalem Delivered]]'' (1594), which was more correct than that of [[Edward Fairfax]]. He also translated [[Juan Huarte de San Juan|Juan de la Huarte]]'s ''Examen de Ingenios'', basing his translation on [[Camillo Camilli (d. 1615)|Camillo Camilli]]'s Italian version.{{sfn|Courtney|1887}} (This book is the first systematic attempt to relate physiology with psychology, though based on the medicine of Galen. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}})

Carew was a member of the [[College of Antiquaries|Elizabethan Society of Antiquaries]], and is particularly known for his ''Survey of Cornwall'' (1602), the second [[English county histories|English county history]] to appear in print. Later editions were published in 1723, 1769 and 1811, and [[Davies Gilbert]] published an index in his ''Cornwall'', vol. 4, pp.&nbsp;381–92. He also published an ''[[Epistle concerning the Excellencies of the English Tongue]]'' (1605).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

Carew served as [[High Sheriff of Cornwall]] (1583 and 1586), and as MP for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] in 1584. He was married to Juliana Arundell, the eldest daughter of [[John Arundell (of Trerice, died 1580)|Sir John Arundell of Trerice]]; their son [[Sir Richard Carew, 1st Baronet|Richard Carew]] was created a baronet in 1641 (see [[Carew baronets]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard CAREW|url=http://www.tudorplace.com.ar/Bios/RichardCarew.htm|publisher=Tudor Place|accessdate=1 July 2011}}{{Unreliable source?|certain=y|self published website; and Jorge H. Castelli is not an expert|date=January 2015}}</ref>

Carew died on 6 November 1620 and was buried in Antony church on 7 November.{{sfn|Carew|Halliday|1969|pp=68-69}}

